 methods to show how teachers at every kind of institution can help students become independent, creative, and active learners.The New College Classroom helps instructors in all disciplines create an environment that is truly conducive to learning. Davidson and Katopodis translate cutting-edge research in learning science and pedagogy into ready-to-use strategies to incorporate into any course. These empirically driven, classroom-tested techniques of active learning—from the participatory syllabus and ungrading to grab-and-go activities for every day of the term—have achieved impressive results at community colleges and research universities, on campus, online, and in hybrid settings.Extensive evidence shows that active-learning tools are more effective than conventional methods of instruction. Davidson and Katopodis explain how and why their approach works and provide detailed case studies of educators successfully applying active-learning techniques in their courses every day, ensuring that their students are better prepared for the world after college.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aActive learningvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aClassroom managementvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aCollege teachingvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aEffective teachingvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aanti-racist pedagogy.  acollege teaching.  acritical pedagogy.  aengaging students.  aequity in the classroom.  aexperimental education.  agrading practices.  ainclusive teaching.  aonline learning.  aparticipatory learning.  aradical pedagogy.  astudent success.  ateam teaching.1 aKatopodis, Christina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078579140uhttps://doi